New Directions in Anti-Angiogenic Therapy for Glioblastoma.

Wang N(1), Jain RK(2), Batchelor TT(3)(4)(5).

Author information:
(1)Stephen E. and Catherine Pappas Center for Neuro-Oncology, Massachusetts 
General Hospital, Boston, MA, USA.
(2)Department of Radiation Oncology, Massachusetts General Hospital, Boston, MA, 
USA.
(3)Stephen E. and Catherine Pappas Center for Neuro-Oncology, Massachusetts 
General Hospital, Boston, MA, USA. tbatchelor@mgh.harvard.edu.
(4)Department of Radiation Oncology, Massachusetts General Hospital, Boston, MA, 
USA. tbatchelor@mgh.harvard.edu.
(5)Department of Hematology/Oncology, Massachusetts General Hospital, Boston, 
MA, USA. tbatchelor@mgh.harvard.edu.

Anti-angiogenic therapy has become an important component in the treatment of 
many solid tumors given the importance of adequate blood supply for tumor growth 
and metastasis. Despite promising preclinical data and early clinical trials, 
anti-angiogenic agents have failed to show a survival benefit in randomized 
controlled trials of patients with glioblastoma. In particular, agents targeting 
vascular endothelial growth factor (VEGF) appear to prolong progression free 
survival, possibly improve quality of life, and decrease steroid usage, yet the 
trials to date have demonstrated no extension of overall survival. In order to 
improve duration of response and convey a survival benefit, additional research 
is still needed to explore alternative pro-angiogenic pathways, mechanisms of 
resistance, combination strategies, and biomarkers to predict therapeutic 
response.

